# When to Use INNER JOIN,  When to Use LEFT OUTER JOIN,  When to Use LEFT OUTER JOIN & When to Use FULL OUTER JOIN  
————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————


— We will Use Inner Join When we are Concerned about Matching Data, If the Data is Not Matching on Any of the Table Discard it


— We will Use Left Outer Join When the Left Table is Very Important for us Even If the Data is Not Matching on the Right Side we still want the Data From the Left Table


— We will Use Right Outer Join When the Right Table is Very Important for us Even If the Data is Not Matching on the Left Side we still want the Data From the Right Table


— We will Use Full Outer Join When Both Left & Right Table is Very Important for us and we don’t want to Lose Any Data.









LEFT OUTER JOIN 
=================

— All the Matching Records From Left and Right Table  Are Considered
+
— All The Non Matching Records In the Left table which does not have the match in the Right Padded with Null





# For Example we have 2 Tables “T-1” & “T-2” which has 100 Records Each and Only 50 Records Are Matching


T-1 Has 100 Records With Column Name  C1,  C2,  C3

T-2 Has 100 Records With Column Name  C4,  C5,  C6



Left Outer Join will Give the  [50 Matching Records]  +  [50 Non Matching Records From the Left Table] 



So the First 50 Records will Have All the 6 Columns from C1 to C6,  But the Other 50 Non Matching Records Will Have Data in the Column C1,  C2,  C3 &  C4,  C5,  C6 will have NULL  [As Shown Below]


C1         C2         C3       C4        C5          C6
C1         C2         C3      NULL    NULL     NULL






